You should remove a test case where N is 0 because there are ties: 0^2 = 1^2 - 1^2 => 1 - 1 difference is minimal, grader only accepts "0 0"
Regarding input size: you should either lower N or make it bigger. If some language can brute force the solution easily, while it's impossible or unreliable on another the first language clearly has an advantage. This damages the competitiveness of CoC. Either brute force should be a viable solution or no one should be able to brute force it.

Also, your solution code is weird: when checking if A * A - B * B == N * N, A becomes very large (25000001 at last test case) which when squared overflows, but it still produces the right answer even though 25000001 * 25000001 is calculated to be 704053377 ¯\_(ツ)_/¯

Here is my C++ solution for reference:

#include <iostream>

using namespace std;

int main()
{
    int N;
    cin >> N;

    if(N == 0) {
        cout << "0 0";
        // cout << "1 1"; ?
    }
    else if(N % 2 == 1) {
        int a = (N * N + 1) / 2;
        cout << a << " " << a - 1 << endl;
    }
    else {
        int a = (N * N + 4) / 4;
        cout << a << " " << a - 2 << endl;
    }
}
